# Security first

When making any code, config, logging, or tooling change, prioritize security before convenience.

## Secrets and keys

- Never hardcode API keys, tokens, passwords, private keys, or credentials in code, tests, docs, commits, or messages.
- Load secrets from environment variables or approved secret stores.
- Do not print or echo secret values in logs, traces, screenshots, or chat responses.
- If a secret is exposed accidentally, rotate it immediately and remove it from tracked files.

## PII and sensitive data

- Treat personal data as sensitive by default and collect/store only what is strictly necessary.
- Never log raw PII (email, phone, address, IDs, payment data, auth artifacts, user content with identifiers).
- Mask, hash, tokenize, or redact sensitive fields in logs and telemetry.
- Use data minimization, retention limits, and least-privilege access for any user data path.

## Hacker-resistant implementation

- Validate and sanitize all untrusted input; prefer allowlists, strict parsing, and typed boundaries.
- Use parameterized queries and safe APIs; never build SQL or shell commands from raw user input.
- Enforce authentication and authorization checks server-side for every protected action.
- Prefer secure defaults: deny by default, explicit allow rules, minimal permissions, and fail closed.
- Keep dependencies updated and avoid introducing known vulnerable packages.

## Before finishing security-relevant work

- Confirm no secrets or PII were added to code, logs, fixtures, or docs.
- Note security assumptions and residual risks if full hardening is out of scope.
